's promise and David''s kingship from the outset. Matthew begins with "God with us" (1:23) and ends with Jesus promising, "I am with you always" (28:20). Matthew 1:22-23 explicitly says the virgin birth fulfills what the Lord spoke by the prophet. Matthew 1:19-24 portrays Joseph''s righteousness as compassionate and responsive to God''s word. Matthew 1 presents Joseph as the legal Davidic father while insisting Jesus''s conception is by the Holy Spirit. Matthew 1 combines genealogy and fulfilled prophecy, setting a pattern the Gospel repeats. Matthew 1:17 presents the genealogy in a deliberate pattern, likely to stress structure and Davidic significance. Matthew 1:16 breaks the repeated genealogy formula and signals Jesus''s unique birth. Matthew 2:1 says Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea. Matthew 2:2 says they saw his star in the east. Matthew 2:11 lists gold, frankincense, and myrrh. Matthew 2:3 says Herod the king was troubled. Matthew 2:1 describes wise men from the east coming to Jerusalem. Matthew 2:12 says they were warned in a dream not to return to Herod. Matthew 2:8 records Herod''s deceptive request. Matthew 2:13-14 says Joseph fled to Egypt with the child and his mother. Matthew 2:3-6 shows Herod asking where the Christ would be born after hearing the wise men''s report. Matthew 2:22 says Joseph feared Archelaus, so he went to Galilee. Matthew 2:17-18 cites Jeremiah to connect the mourning in Bethlehem with Israel''s historic sorrow. Matthew 2:15 cites, "Out of Egypt I called my son," connecting Jesus with Israel''s story. Matthew 2 contrasts Gentile worshipers with Herod''s violent hostility. Matthew 2:9-10 presents the star as divine guidance leading the wise men to Jesus. Matthew 2:4-6 shows religious leaders able to cite the text but absent from the act of worship. Matthew 2:3-16 contrasts Herod''s murderous fear with the magi''s worship. Matthew 2:2-3 contrasts the wise men''s worshipful intent with Jerusalem''s disturbed response. Matthew 2 echoes the pattern of Pharaoh''s threat in Exodus, with Herod trying to kill the child. Matthew 2 shows Gentiles coming to worship the Jewish Messiah, anticipating the Gospel''s global horizon. Matthew 2:5-6, 15, 17-18, and 23 all stress fulfillment of Scripture. Matthew 2 repeatedly uses dreams to direct the wise men and Joseph, showing divine rule over events. Matthew 2:15 presents Jesus as recapitulating Israel''s story through the Egypt motif. Matthew 2:15 applies "Out of Egypt I called my son" to Jesus, portraying him as embodying Israel''s calling. Matthew 2 contrasts worship and hostility without making ethnicity the sole explanation of response. Matthew 2:23 links Jesus with Nazareth, shaping expectations about the Messiah''s lowly and unexpected profile. Matthew 3:4 describes John''s clothing as camel''s hair and a leather belt. Matthew 3:4 says John''s food was locusts and wild honey. Matthew 3:16 says the heavens were opened when Jesus came up from the water. Matthew 3:2 records John''s message. Matthew 3:1 introduces John the Baptizer preaching in the wilderness. Matthew 3:11 says the one coming after John is mightier than he. Matthew 3:7 records John''s sharp rebuke. Matthew 3:6 says they were baptized by John while confessing their sins. Matthew 3:8 says, "Bring forth therefore fruit worthy of repentance." Matthew 3:14 says John tried to stop Jesus, saying he needed baptism from Jesus. Matthew 3:10 uses the axe imagery to warn of imminent judgment. Matthew 3:11-12 combines Spirit imagery with fire and chaff-burning judgment. Matthew 3:16 depicts the Spirit descending on Jesus as a visible sign of divine approval and mission. Matthew 3:15 presents Jesus''s baptism as part of fulfilling God''s righteous will. Matthew 3:9 rejects reliance on descent from Abraham as a substitute for true repentance. Matthew 3:7-10 critiques reliance on appearance, ancestry, and status apart from real repentance. Matthew 3:3 quotes Isaiah to identify John as the preparatory voice. Matthew 3 introduces themes of fruit, repentance, and hypocrisy that resurface throughout the Gospel. Matthew 3:16-17 presents Jesus in the water, the Spirit descending, and the Father''s voice from heaven. Matthew 3 closes the preparation period and marks Jesus out before his public ministry begins. Matthew 3 introduces themes of repentance, fruit, and judgment that intensify in Jesus''s later teaching. Matthew 3 moves from John''s preaching to Jesus''s baptism and divine affirmation. Matthew 3:17, "This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased," resonates with both Psalm 2:7 and Isaiah 42:1. Matthew 3:16-17 presents the opened heavens as the setting for the Spirit''s descent and the Father''s declaration. Matthew 3:9 undermines confidence in ancestry by emphasizing God''s sovereign power to create a people for himself. Matthew 4:2 says Jesus fasted forty days and forty nights in the wilderness. Matthew 4:17 records the start of Jesus''s preaching in Galilee. Matthew 4:23 summarizes Jesus''s Galilean ministry. Matthew 4:20 says they immediately left their nets and followed Jesus. Matthew 4:12 says Jesus withdrew into Galilee after hearing that John had been arrested. Matthew 4:10 gives Jesus''s scriptural answer. Matthew 4:4 says man shall not live by bread alone. Matthew 4:19 records Jesus calling them to become fishers of men. Matthew 4:8 says the devil showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory. Matthew 4:3 records the temptation to turn stones into bread. Matthew 4 moves from victory over temptation to kingdom healing ministry. Matthew 4:5-7 contrasts trust with presumptuous testing of God. Matthew 4:4, 4:7, and 4:10 show Jesus replying with words from Scripture. Matthew 4:15-16 cites Isaiah to interpret Jesus''s move to Galilee. Matthew 4:18-22 shows immediate response to Jesus''s call. Matthew 4 intentionally echoes Israel''s wilderness story through Jesus''s obedience. Matthew 4 ends with crowds gathering around Jesus before the sermon begins in chapter 5. Matthew 4:17-25 combines preaching, calling disciples, and healing. Matthew 4:20 and 4:22 stress their immediate response. Matthew 4:13-16 presents Jesus''s move to Galilee as fulfillment of Isaiah''s light prophecy. Matthew 4:8-10 ties worship and kingdom directly together. The temptations in Matthew 4 clarify the false kinds of messiahship Jesus rejects. Matthew 4 joins temptation victory, kingdom proclamation, calling disciples, and widespread healing into the opening pattern of Jesus''s ministry. Matthew 4 portrays the kingdom as already active in Jesus''s ministry. Matthew 4 repeatedly shows Jesus answering temptation with Scripture. Matthew 5:5 says the meek shall inherit the earth. Matthew 5:5 says the meek shall inherit the earth. Matthew 5:14 calls the disciples the light of the world. Matthew 5:15 says a lamp is put on a stand to give light. Matthew 5:3 says, ''Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.'' Matthew 5:44 gives this command. Matthew 5:21-22 intensifies the commandment against murder to heart-level anger. Matthew 5:23-24 tells the worshiper to be reconciled first. Matthew 5:17 says Jesus came not to abolish but to fulfill. Matthew 5:13-14 calls the disciples salt of the earth and light of the world. Matthew 5:21-30 moves from outward acts to anger and lust at the heart level. Matthew 5:44-48 grounds enemy-love in the Father''s perfection. Matthew 5:21-30 deepens the commandments to motives and desires. Matthew 5:13-16 uses salt and light as public kingdom metaphors. Matthew 5:33-37 calls for simple, truthful speech. Matthew 5 moves from kingdom blessing to kingdom righteousness. Matthew 5:17 says Jesus came not to destroy the Law or the Prophets but to fulfill them. Matthew 5:13-16 stresses visible good works and witness before others. Matthew 5:20 and the following examples define deeper righteousness. Matthew 5:17-20 centers on fulfillment as the frame for Jesus''s teaching. Matthew 5 begins with