us. The chapter repeatedly centers secret communion, trust, and desire before God. Matthew 6:25-34 uses birds and lilies to show the Father''s care and to oppose anxiety. Matthew 6:12 and 6:14-15 tie divine forgiveness and human forgiveness closely together. Matthew 7:1-5 warns against hypocritical judgment. Matthew 7:7 says to ask, seek, and knock. Matthew 7:13-14 contrasts the narrow gate leading to life with the broad way leading to destruction. Matthew 7:3 refers to the speck in a brother''s eye. Matthew 7:12 gives the Golden Rule. Matthew 7:15-20 says false prophets are known by their fruits. Matthew 7:5 says to remove the log from your own eye first. Matthew 7:7 says to ask, seek, and knock. Matthew 7:25 says it did not fall because it was founded on the rock. Matthew 7:28-29 says the crowds were astonished because he taught with authority. Matthew 7:21-23 warns that not all who claim Jesus as Lord truly belong to him. Matthew 7:13-14 contrasts the broad and narrow ways. Matthew 7:16-20 says people are known by their fruits. Matthew 7:3-5 exposes hypocrisy in moral judgment. Matthew 7:24-27 contrasts doing Jesus''s words with merely hearing them. Matthew 7 weaves together prayer, ethical vision, discernment, and obedience. Matthew 7:15-27 repeatedly warns against deceptive appearances. Matthew 7:24-27 contrasts hearing and doing with hearing and not doing. Matthew 7:24-29 places decisive weight on Jesus''s words and authority. Matthew 7:16-20 uses fruit as a moral and spiritual indicator. Matthew 7 holds together asking the Father and obeying Jesus''s teaching. Matthew 7 closes the sermon with urgent contrasts and a call to obey. The wise builder in Matthew 7 embodies practical obedience to Jesus. Matthew 7:24-29 frames response to Jesus''s words as foundational. Matthew 7:28-29 says the crowds were amazed because Jesus taught with authority. Matthew 8:26 says Jesus rebuked the winds and the sea. Matthew 8:31 asks Jesus to send them into the herd of pigs. Matthew 8:5-6 says a centurion came asking help for his servant. Matthew 8:2-3 says Jesus touched and cleansed a leper. Matthew 8:5-13 tells of the centurion''s servant being healed. Matthew 8:26 records Jesus rebuking the winds and the sea. Matthew 8:11 speaks of many coming from east and west to the kingdom feast. Matthew 8:8 expresses the centurion''s confidence in Jesus''s word. Matthew 8:34 says the town begged Jesus to leave their region. Matthew 8:15 says she arose and served him. Matthew 8:26-27 shows the sea obeying Jesus''s rebuke. Matthew 8:34 shows the town preferring Jesus''s departure after the exorcism. Matthew 8:8-10 highlights the centurion''s confidence in Jesus''s authority to heal at a distance. Matthew 8:10-12 highlights the centurion''s extraordinary faith and its contrast with unbelief. Matthew 8:3 shows Jesus touching and cleansing the leper. Matthew 8 moves across sickness, distance, nature, and demons under Jesus''s authority. Matthew 8-9 together form a broad authority section. Matthew 8 moves from healing to exorcism to calming the storm, showing broad authority. Matthew 8 includes both miracles and scenes exposing the disciples'' fears. Matthew 8:11-12 uses the centurion setting to speak about kingdom inclusion and exclusion. The centurion episode in Matthew 8 makes this explicit. Matthew 8 repeatedly emphasizes the efficacy of Jesus''s authoritative word. Matthew 8:34 says the whole city asked Jesus to depart after the deliverance. The disciples and the town both respond to Jesus''s power, but in very different ways. Matthew 8:27 crystallizes the chapter''s rising sense of Jesus''s identity. Matthew 9:2 records Jesus first pronouncing forgiveness. Matthew 9:37 says the harvest is plentiful. Matthew 9:20-21 tells of the woman touching Jesus''s garment. Matthew 9:9 says Jesus called Matthew from the tax booth. Matthew 9:9 says Jesus saw a man called Matthew sitting at the tax office and called him. Matthew 9:37 says the harvest is plentiful but the laborers are few. Matthew 9:13 says, ''I desire mercy, and not sacrifice.'' Matthew 9:26 says the report went through all that district. Matthew 9:27 says the blind men cried out, ''Have mercy on us, Son of David.'' Matthew 9:3 says the scribes judged Jesus blasphemous for forgiving sins. Matthew 9:36 portrays the crowds as sheep without a shepherd. Matthew 9:10-13 explains Jesus''s table fellowship through his mission to sinners. Matthew 9:18-26 interweaves the stories around trust in Jesus. Matthew 9:2-8 links the healing with authority to forgive sins. Matthew 9:6 ties the healing to authority to forgive sins. Matthew 9 moves from individual restoration to the need for wider labor in the harvest. Matthew 9:37-38 leads directly into the mission discourse of chapter 10. Matthew 9:12-13 says the healthy do not need a physician but the sick do, and Jesus came to call sinners. Matthew 8-9 forms a broad authority section culminating in mission. Matthew 9:12-13 uses the physician image to explain Jesus''s mission. Across Matthew 9, characters respond by believing, following, receiving mercy, and joining the mission movement. Matthew 9 shows layered mercy across many forms of brokenness. Matthew 9 culminates in prayer for more laborers for the plentiful harvest. Matthew 9:36-38 turns from healing crowds to praying for laborers for the harvest. The blind men in Matthew 9 use ''Son of David'' as a messianic plea for mercy. Matthew 10:1-4 names the twelve apostles. Matthew 10:5-6 tells them to go to the lost sheep of Israel. Matthew 10:1 says Jesus gave them authority over unclean spirits and disease. Matthew 10:7 gives their message. Matthew 10:42 says even a cup of cold water given to a disciple will be rewarded. Matthew 10:5-6 says they were sent first to Israel''s lost sheep. Matthew 10:38 says whoever does not take his cross is not worthy of Jesus. Matthew 10:19-20 says the Spirit will give them what to speak. Matthew 10:16 gives this instruction. Matthew 10:9 tells them not to take money. Matthew 10:16 speaks of danger and calls for wisdom as serpents and innocence as doves. Matthew 10:16 frames mission as vulnerable and contested. Matthew 10:39 gives this paradox of discipleship. Matthew 10:34-37 emphasizes supreme allegiance to Jesus over family ties. Matthew 10:5-6 sets an initial focus on Israel without exhausting Matthew''s later global horizon. Matthew 10 holds together dependence, hardship, and reward within one mission discourse. Matthew 10:37-39 ties discipleship to taking the cross and valuing Jesus above all. Themes of opposition, confession, and endurance introduced here continue throughout Matthew. Matthew 10 prepares the disciples for a mission shaped by conflict and confession. Matthew 10:26-31 grounds courage in God''s knowledge and care. Matthew 10:29-31 grounds courage in the Father''s care for sparrows and his children. Matthew 10 presents mission as relationally tied to Jesus and supported by divine care. Matthew 10:40-42 ties reception of disciples to reception of Jesus and the Father. Matthew 10:42 says even a cup of cold water given to a disciple will not lose its reward. Matthew 10:38 brings cruciform discipleship into focus well before the passion narrative. Matthew 11:20-24 rebukes those cities. Matthew 11:7 asks if they went out to see a reed shaken by the wind. Matthew 11:28 gives this invitation. Matthew 11:3 records the question from John''s disciples. Matthew 11:3 records John''s question through his disciples. Matthew 11:25 says the Father reveals these things to little children. Matthew 11:11 says none born of women is greater than John. Matthew 11:30 says, ''My yoke is easy, and my burden is light.'' Matthew 11:28 invites the weary to come to Jesus for rest. Matthew 11:4-5 answers with messianic signs drawn from Jesus''s ministry. Matthew 11:4-5 lists signs like the blind seeing and the poor having good news preached to them. Matthew 11:20-24 rebukes cities that saw mighty works but did not repent. Matthew 11:25-27 emphasizes revelatory dependence on the Father and the Son. Matthew 11:4-6 points to Jesus''s works as evidence of his identity. Matthew 11:28-30 centers rest in coming to Jesus himself. Matthew 11 unfolds from identity to judgment to invitation. Matthew 11 presents both messianic fulfillment and stubborn unbelief. Matthew 11 combines signs, woes, revelation, and invitation. Matthew 11:20-24 condemns those cities for failing to repent despite mighty works. Matthew 11:9-10 cites prophecy to define John''s role. Matthew 11:25-30 joins divine revelation to little ones with Jesus''s invitation to rest. Matthew 11:25-30 joins revelation in the Son with invitation to rest in him. Matthew 11:29-30 links Jesus''s gentleness with the yoke he gives. The city woes in Matthew 11 make this point directly. Matthew 11:11 contrasts John''s greatness with the surpassing privilege of the kingdom. Matthew 12:50 defines Jesus''s true family that way. Matthew 12:1-2 says the disciples plucked grain on the Sabbath. Matthew 12:1-2 records the disciples plucking grain on the Sabbath. Matthew 12:10 says the man had a withered hand. Matthew 12:39-40 says no sign would be given except the sign of Jonah. Matthew 12:24 gives that accusation. Matthew 12:7 repeats, ''I desire mercy, and not sacrifice.'' Matthew 12:42 mentions the queen of the South. Matthew 12:39-40 says only the sign of Jonah would be given. Matthew 12:8 says the Son of Man is Lord of the Sabbath. Matthew 12:46-50 redefines family around doing the Father''s will. Matthew 12:25-29 answers the Beelzebul accusation logically and theologically. Matthew 12:7 and 12 emphasize mercy and doing good on the Sabbath. Matthew 12:31-32 places the warning in the context of attributing God''s work to evil. Matthew 12:1-13 ties Sabbath interpretation to mercy and Jesus''s lordship. Matthew 12 is a concentrated chapter of conflict and revelation around Jesus''s authority. Matthew 12:6, 41, and 42 make those explicit comparisons. Matthew 12:14 shows the Pharisees plotting to destroy Jesus. Matthew 12:40 links Jonah''s three days to the Son of Man''s coming burial and rising. Matthew 12:22-32 places the warning in the context of attributing Jesus''s Spirit-empowered work to evil. Matthew 12:48-50 says whoever does the Father''s will is Jesus''s brother, sister, and mother. Matthew 12 repeatedly pits mercy against hypocritical rigidity. Matthew 12 is a crucial turning point of conflict and revelation. Matthew 12:33-37 links the heart, words, and final account. Matthew 12''s greater-than sayings and family redefinition center everything on Jesus. Matthew 13:44 compares the kingdom to treasure hidden in a field. Matthew 13:55 says they called him the carpenter''s son. Matthew 13:8 says seed on good soil bore fruit. Matthew 13:8 and 13:23 describe good soil as hearing and bearing fruit. Matthew 13:1-2 says Jesus taught by the sea from a boat. Matthew 13:47 compares the kingdom to a net cast into the sea. Matthew 13:25 says the enemy sowed weeds among the wheat. Matthew 13:31-32 says it becomes a tree where birds nest. Matthew 13:44-46 compares the kingdom to treasure and a pearl. Matthew 13:10-15 explains the purpose of parables in relation to hardened hearing. Matthew 13:53-58 ends with Nazareth''s offense and unbelief. Matthew 13:24-30 and 36-43 teach delayed separation until the end of the age. Matthew 13:44-46 emphasizes the kingdom''s value and joyful sacrifice. Matthew 13:10-17 explains the mixed purpose of parables. Matthew 13:18-23 and 36-43 show Jesus privately interpreting parables. Matthew 13''s parables together offer a many-sided portrait of the kingdom. The discourse anticipates the rejection and mixed responses that continue in Matthew. Matthew 13:24-30 and 13:36-43 explain separation at the end of the age. Matthew 13 is the Gospel''s central parable discourse on the kingdom. Matthew 13:10-17 stresses differing responses to revelation. Matthew 13 repeatedly balances present hiddenness with future harvest. The weeds and net parables both end with final sorting and judgment. Matthew 13:53-58 ends with Nazareth taking offense and Jesus doing few mighty works there. The chapter moves from soils to Nazareth''s offense as contrasting responses. Matthew 13 shows Jesus as the one who reveals the kingdom''s secret to disciples. Matthew 14:17 says the disciples had five loaves and two fish. Matthew 14:28 records Peter''s request. Matthew 14:33 records their confession. Matthew 14:1-2 says Herod thought Jesus was John raised from the dead. Matthew 14:10 says Herod sent and beheaded John in prison. Matthew 14:20 says twelve baskets full of leftovers were taken up. Matthew 14:17 says they had five loaves and two fish. Matthew 14:19 says Jesus looked up to heaven, blessed, and broke the loaves. Matthew 14:30 says Peter became afraid and began to sink. Matthew 14:3-4 explains John''s imprisonment. Matthew 14 connects John''s death with Herod''s fear and the dangerous climate around Jesus. Matthew 14:28-31 shows Peter sinking when he becomes afraid and doubts. Matthew 14:29-31 links Peter''s fear with his sinking. Matthew 14:33 records worship and confession after the sea miracle. Matthew 14:13-21 presents Jesus as compassionate provider for the multitude. Matthew 14 combines martyrdom, provision, and divine-like authority. Matthew 14 presents Jesus feeding the crowd and then walking on the sea, showing compassion and authority. Matthew 14 evokes wilderness provision and divine authority over the waters. Matthew 14 tests discipleship through hunger, storm, and fear. Matthew 14:23 places solitary prayer between the feeding and sea miracle. The feeding and the healings in Gennesaret show glory expressed as mercy. Matthew 14 shows faith tested in multiple settings, especially Peter on the water. Herod''s violence is contrasted with Jesus''s compassionate authority throughout Matthew 14. Matthew 14:33 records the disciples worshiping Jesus and calling him the Son of God. Matthew 14:33 is a climactic confession in response to Jesus''s works. Matthew 15:20 says eating with unwashed hands does not defile a person. Matthew 15:22 asks mercy for her daughter, who was severely demonized. Matthew 15:17-20 says evil thoughts and sins come out of the heart and defile a person. Matthew 15:21-28 highlights her persistent, humble, and effective faith. Matthew 15 contrasts heart-defilement teaching with compassionate healing and feeding, including a Gentile woman''s faith. Matthew 16:16 gives Peter''s confession. Matthew 16:24 says disciples must deny themselves and take up their cross. Matthew 16:12 says the disciples understood he meant the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees. Matthew 16:21-23 shows Peter confessing Jesus rightly yet rejecting the prediction of suffering. Matthew 16 combines Peter''s confession and keys with Jesus''s call to deny self and lose life to find it. Matthew 17:3 says Moses and Elijah appeared talking with Jesus. Matthew 17:5 records the Father''s voice telling the disciples to listen to Jesus. Matthew 17:19-21 connects their failure with little faith and prayer. Matthew 17 follows the prediction of suffering with a revelation of Jesus''s glory and sonship. Matthew 17:24-27 says the sons are free, yet Jesus pays so as not to cause offense. Matthew 18:3-4 says greatness belongs to the one who becomes humble like a child. Matthew 18:21-22 answers Peter''s question with seventy times seven. Matthew 18:23-35 ends by warning against refusing mercy after receiving mercy. Matthew 18:10-14 stresses that the Father does not will that one of these little ones perish. Matthew 18:15 says the goal is to gain your brother. Matthew 19:4 cites creation: God made them male and female. Matthew 19:16-22 records the rich young man''s question. Matthew 19:21-22 shows the man leaving sorrowful because he had great possessions. Matthew 19 ties covenant faithfulness, childlike reception, and costly discipleship together. Matthew 19:27-30 closes with promised reward and the reversal saying that leads into chapter 20. Matthew 20:1-7 describes workers hired into a vineyard throughout the day. Matthew 20:30-31 says the blind men cried, ''Lord, have mercy on us, Son of David!'' Matthew 20:13-15 centers on the master''s right to be generous. Matthew 20:25-28 contrasts Gentile rulers with servant greatness among Jesus''s followers. Matthew 20:17-28 joins the passion prediction with the teaching that the Son of Man came to serve and give his life as a ransom. Matthew 21:5-7 presents Jesus entering Jerusalem on a donkey. Matthew 21:12 says Jesus drove out those buying and selling in the temple. Matthew 21:18-22 uses the fig tree in a context of fruitlessness and judgment. Matthew 21:28-46 indicts leaders who would not obey John and who reject the Son. Matthew 21:42 applies Psalm language to Jesus as the rejected yet chosen cornerstone. Matthew 22:2 begins with a parable about a king giving a wedding feast for his son. Matthew 22:21 says to render to Caesar what is Caesar''s and to God what is God''s. Matthew 22:29 rebukes the Sadducees for misunderstanding Scripture and God''s power. Matthew 22:37-40 says all the Law and the Prophets depend on these two commands. Matthew 22:41-46 uses Psalm 110 to show the Messiah''s superiority to simple descent categories. Matthew 23:5-7 says they loved public honor, greetings, and titles. Matthew 23:27 compares them to whitewashed tombs. Matthew 23 repeatedly contrasts outward appearance with inward corruption. Matthew 23:23 says they neglected justice, mercy, and faithfulness. Matthew 23:37 laments Jerusalem for killing the prophets and refusing to be gathered. Matthew 24:2 foretells the temple''s destruction. Matthew 24:36 says no one knows the day or hour except the Father. Matthew 24 presents these as birth pains and warnings, calling disciples to watchfulness. Matthew 24:37-39 compares ordinary life before the flood with unexpected judgment at the Son of Man''s coming. Matthew 24:45-51 ends by contrasting faithful readiness with careless delay. Matthew 25:1-13 contrasts wise virgins with oil and foolish ones without it. Matthew 25:21 and 25:23 commend the faithful servants with those words. Matthew 25 links watchfulness with responsible stewardship while awaiting the master''s coming. Matthew 25:34-40 commends acts of mercy done to the least of these. Matthew 25 weaves together readiness, entrusted responsibility, and final separation. Matthew 26:14-15 says Judas agreed to betray Jesus for thirty pieces of silver. Matthew 26:27-28 explains the cup in covenant and forgiveness language. Matthew 26:39 shows Jesus praying, ''Not as I will, but as you will.'' Matthew 26 links burial preparation, covenant meal, and obedient surrender. Matthew 26:31-35 and 69-75 frame Peter''s confidence and collapse. Matthew 27:21 says the crowd chose Barabbas. Matthew 27:54 records the centurion''s confession. Matthew 27:51 links Jesus''s death with the veil being torn from top to bottom. Matthew 27 highlights mock kingship language even as Jesus fulfills the path to the cross. Matthew 27:57-61 gives a concrete burial account in Joseph''s new tomb. Matthew 28:1 names Mary Magdalene and the other Mary at the tomb. Matthew 28:18 introduces the commission with Jesus''s universal authority. Matthew 28:5-6 announces the resurrection plainly. Matthew 28:11-15 reports the bribery as an attempted counter-story to the resurrection. Matthew 1:23 calls Jesus Immanuel, and Matthew 28:20 ends with Jesus promising to be with his disciples always. The Pharisees and scribes objected that Jesus'' disciples ate bread without first washing their hands according to tradition. Jesus granted the Canaanite woman''s request and healed her daughter from that hour. Jesus used seven loaves, along with a few small fish, to feed the crowd of four thousand. After everyone ate, the disciples took up seven baskets full of broken pieces. Jesus taught that defilement comes from the heart and is expressed in evil words and actions, not from unwashed hands. She addressed Jesus as ''Lord, Son of David'' while asking mercy for her demon-oppressed daughter. Jesus listed evil thoughts, murders, adulteries, and other sins as proceeding from the heart. Jesus said he had compassion because the crowd had remained with him for three days and had nothing to eat. Jesus spoke of not taking the children''s bread and throwing it to the little dogs, and the woman responded humbly and faithfully. Jesus named a list of heart-sins including murders, adulteries, sexual sins, thefts, false testimony, and blasphemies. Jesus noted that many had come from far away and might faint if sent away hungry. After feeding the four thousand, Jesus entered the boat and came into the borders of Magdala. Jesus rebuked them for allowing vows like ''Whatever help you might have received from me is given to God,'' which undermined honoring parents. Jesus said they were blind guides, and if the blind lead the blind, both fall into a pit. The crowds brought the lame, blind, mute, maimed, and many others, and Jesus healed them. The crowd marveled and glorified the God of Israel after witnessing the healings. Her humble and faithful reply showed confidence in Jesus'' mercy, and he praised her great faith. Jesus quoted Isaiah: the people honor God with their lips, but their heart is far from him. Jesus'' compassion for the hungry crowd moved him to provide food rather than dismiss them weak and fasting. Jesus said every plant not planted by his Father would be uprooted, highlighting the temporary nature of false religious teaching. The Pharisees and Sadducees came testing Jesus and asked him to show them a sign from heaven. Simon Peter made that confession at Caesarea Philippi. Jesus said that anyone who wanted to follow him must deny himself, take up his cross, and follow. Jesus warned them about the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees, meaning their teaching. The disciples reasoned among themselves that Jesus said this because they had brought no bread. Jesus asked his disciples who people said he was when they came into the region of Caesarea Philippi. Jesus said, ''On this rock I will build my assembly,'' often rendered ''church.'' After Peter''s confession, Jesus began openly teaching about his coming suffering, death, and resurrection. Jesus refused their demand for another sign and said only the sign of Jonah would be given. The disciples finally understood that Jesus was warning them about the doctrine or teaching of those groups. Jesus promised that the gates of Hades would not overpower the assembly he would build. Jesus asked what profit there is in gaining the whole world and forfeiting one''s soul or life. Jesus told Peter that flesh and blood had not revealed this to him, but his Father in heaven. Peter took Jesus aside and rebuked him, saying this would never happen. Jesus sharply corrected Peter because he was setting his mind on human interests rather than God''s. Jesus told Peter he would give him the keys of the Kingdom, with binding and loosing language attached. Jesus directed them not to publicize that he was the Messiah at that stage. Jesus taught that the Son of Man would come with his angels and render to each according to what he had done. Jesus said some present would not taste death until they saw the Son of Man coming in his Kingdom. He pointed to the feeding miracles so they would understand he was not warning them about ordinary bread shortages. Jesus was transfigured before the three disciples on the mountain. Moses and Elijah appeared talking with Jesus on the mountain. A father brought his afflicted son to Jesus after the disciples had been unable to heal him. Jesus told Peter to catch a fish and find a coin in its mouth for the tax payment. The Father identified Jesus as his beloved Son and commanded the disciples to listen to him. Peter proposed making three tents or shelters: one for Jesus, one for Moses, and one for Elijah. Jesus connected their failure to little faith and then taught about faith like a mustard seed. The collectors of the didrachma tax came to Peter in Capernaum. Matthew says Jesus'' face shone like the sun and his garments became white as the light. The voice terrified them, and they fell face down until Jesus touched them. Jesus told them to tell no one the vision until the Son of Man had risen from the dead. Jesus explained that Elijah had already come, and the disciples understood he was speaking of John the Baptist. Jesus said faith as small as a mustard seed could tell a mountain to move, and it would move. Jesus again told the disciples about his coming betrayal, death, and resurrection. Jesus said the sons are free, but they would pay in order not to offend or cause stumbling. Jesus gave Peter specific instructions that led to the miraculous provision of the coin. Jesus took only Peter, James, and John up the mountain where he was transfigured. The disciples asked about the scribal teaching concerning Elijah''s coming, and Jesus connected it to John the Baptist. Jesus lamented the unbelief around him by calling it a faithless and perverse generation. Jesus told Peter to give the coin ''for me and you,'' covering both of them. Jesus placed a little child in their midst and taught that humility like a child marks greatness in the Kingdom. Jesus told Peter that forgiveness should not stop at seven times but extend seventy times seven. Jesus described a shepherd leaving ninety-nine sheep to seek one that had gone astray. Jesus said it would be better to have a great millstone hung around one''s neck than to cause one of these little ones to stumble. The first step in Matthew 18 discipline is a private conversation aimed at gaining your brother. Jesus instructed the offended person to return with one or two others so every word may be established. Jesus used severe imagery to stress the seriousness of dealing with sin. In the parable, the lord had compassion and forgave the servant''s enormous debt. Jesus said that the angels of these little ones continually behold the face of his Father in heaven. Persistent refusal to listen even to the church results in treatment as an outsider. Jesus promised the Father''s response in the context of gathered agreement and discipline. Though he had been forgiven a huge debt, he grabbed his fellow servant and demanded repayment. Jesus used strong comparisons to show the radical seriousness of dealing with sin that causes stumbling. The master called him wicked and handed him over in judgment because he had shown no mercy. Jesus concluded that it is not the Father''s will that one of these little ones should perish. Jesus used binding and loosing language in the context of church discipline and agreement before God. Peter asked whether forgiving seven times was enough, and Jesus expanded the answer far beyond that. Their question about greatness led Jesus to teach humility using a little child. Jesus promised his presence among those gathered in his name. The goal of the process is restoration, and Jesus says that listening means you have gained your brother. The Pharisees came testing Jesus with a question about divorce. Jesus told the disciples to let the little children come to him and not forbid them. Matthew 19 records the rich young ruler asking about eternal life. Jesus compared it to a camel going through the eye of a needle. Jesus cited Genesis, saying the Creator made them male and female from the beginning. Jesus said Moses permitted divorce because of human hardness of heart, but it was not so from the beginning. Jesus blessed the children by laying his hands on them. He went away grieving because he had many possessions. Jesus said that divorcing a wife and marrying another is adultery except in the case of sexual immorality. The disciples thought the strictness of the marriage bond made singleness seem preferable. Jesus listed commandments from the law and included loving one''s neighbor as oneself. When the disciples asked who could be saved, Jesus answered that with men it is impossible, but with God all things are possible. Jesus quoted Genesis to show the permanence and unity of marriage. Peter contrasted the disciples'' sacrifice with the rich man''s refusal and asked what their reward would be. Jesus promised a place of honor and judgment for the twelve in the regeneration. Jesus closed the chapter with a warning that human rankings are often reversed in God''s Kingdom. Jesus described three kinds of eunuchs and said the one able to receive the saying should receive it. The children were brought so Jesus would place his hands on them and pray for them. Jesus exposed the man''s heart by calling him to surrender wealth, give to the poor, and follow him. Jesus promised abundant reward and eternal life to those who sacrifice for his name. Jesus told a parable about laborers hired at different hours to work in a vineyard. The mother of James and John came with her sons asking for places of honor in the Kingdom. Matthew records two blind men sitting by the road who cried out for mercy. The blind men cried, ''Have mercy on us, Lord, Son of David!'' The landowner agreed with the first workers for a denarius for the day. Jesus again told the twelve that he would be condemned, mocked, crucified, and raised the third day. Jesus said whoever wants to become great must be a servant. Jesus touched their eyes, and immediately they received sight and followed him. They complained because the late workers were made equal to them in pay. Jesus asked whether they were able to drink the cup he was about to drink, referring to suffering. Jesus contrasted worldly rulers with his own mission of service and sacrificial redemption. The crowd tried to silence them, but they cried out even more loudly. The master defended his generosity by saying he was free to do what he wanted with his own money. Jesus said those places were not his to grant arbitrarily but belonged to those prepared by the Father. The ten became angry with the two brothers over their request for honor. Jesus rejected power-seeking leadership and redefined greatness as humble service. The parable highlights God''s surprising reversals, echoing Jesus'' saying about the last and the first. When Jesus asked what they wanted, they requested that their eyes be opened. After Jesus healed them, the two blind men followed him. Jesus said whoever wants to be first among his disciples must become a servant, even a slave, to others. Jesus entered Jerusalem riding on a donkey, fulfilling prophecy. The crowds shouted ''Hosanna to the Son of David'' as Jesus entered the city. Jesus cleansed the temple by driving out those buying and selling there. The fig tree withered after Jesus pronounced judgment on it. Matthew links the triumphal entry to Zechariah''s prophecy of Zion''s king coming humbly on a donkey. Jesus said God''s house should be called a house of prayer, not a den of robbers. After cleansing the temple, Jesus healed the blind and the lame who came to him there. Jesus answered their question with one about the origin of John''s baptism. Jesus used the withered fig tree to teach about believing prayer and mountain-moving faith. The son who repented and obeyed did the father''s will. In the parable, the tenants cast the son out of the vineyard and killed him. Jesus quoted Psalm 118 about the rejected stone becoming the cornerstone. Fearing the crowd and unwilling to admit the truth, they answered that they did not know. Jesus said repentant outcasts were entering before leaders who rejected John''s message. Jesus warned that the Kingdom would be taken from unfruitful leaders and given to others who bear fruit. The leaders understood he meant them, but fear of the people restrained them. Children continued proclaiming Jesus as David''s Son in the temple, provoking the leaders. Jesus appealed to Scripture to justify the children''s praise. Jesus left the city and lodged in Bethany. Jesus taught that if they believed, they would receive whatever they asked in prayer. Jesus compared the Kingdom of Heaven to a king who gave a wedding feast for his son. Jesus said to render to Caesar what belongs to Caesar, and to God what belongs to God. The Sadducees, who deny the resurrection, posed the question about the woman with seven husbands. Jesus said the greatest commandment is wholehearted love for God. Those first invited would not come, and some seized and killed the servants. Jesus asked whose image and inscription were on the tribute coin. Jesus corrected the Sadducees by saying that in the resurrection people neither marry nor are given in marriage. Jesus paired love of neighbor with love of God as the second great commandment. The unprepared guest was expelled, showing that invitation alone is not enough. Jesus rebuked the Sadducees for misunderstanding both Scripture and God''s power. Jesus used God''s present-tense declaration to Moses to show that God is not the God of the dead but of the living. Jesus asked what they thought about the Christ and whose son he is. The king opened the invitation broadly and filled the hall with guests gathered from the roads. Jesus'' reply avoided the political trap and exposed their insincerity. Jesus summarized the law and the prophets under the twin commands of love for God and neighbor. Jesus quoted, ''The Lord said to my Lord,'' from Psalm 110. Jesus concluded the parable with the warning that many are invited, but few are chosen. The crowds were astonished by Jesus'' authoritative answer. Jesus'' question silenced them, and from then on no one dared question him further. Jesus paired Caesar''s due with the higher duty of rendering to God what belongs to God. Jesus warned against following the hypocritical example of the scribes and Pharisees. Jesus said they bind heavy burdens on others while refusing to lift them with a finger. Jesus taught that everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, and the humble will be exalted. Jesus lamented over Jerusalem as the city that kills the prophets and stones those sent to her. Jesus told his followers not to seek exalted titles because they have one Teacher and one Father in heaven. He criticized their love of status, greetings, and chief places. Jesus said they tithed tiny herbs while neglecting justice, mercy, and faithfulness. Jesus exposed their hypocrisy with images of cups clean outside and tombs beautiful outwardly but full of uncleanness. One woe says they shut the Kingdom of Heaven in people''s faces and neither enter nor allow others to enter. Jesus said their proselytes became even more fitting for judgment than they were. Jesus rebuked them for focusing on minor tithes while neglecting the law''s weightier matters. Jesus said they strain out a gnat but swallow a camel. Though they honored the prophets'' tombs, their actions showed they shared the same spirit as their fathers. Jesus pictured himself as a mother hen longing to gather and protect Jerusalem''s children. Jesus pronounced desolation on their house as part of his judgment on Jerusalem. Jesus used severe language to expose the depth of their hypocrisy and coming judgment. Jesus distinguished between the authority of Moses'' teaching and the hypocrisy of their conduct. Jesus noted their outward honor toward the dead prophets while exposing their inward hostility to God''s messengers. Jesus said Jerusalem would not see him again until that future acknowledgment. Jesus again defined greatness by service rather than status. Jesus foretold the temple''s destruction, saying not one stone would be left upon another. Jesus warned of wars and rumors of wars as part of the birth pains before the end. Jesus said people carried on normally in Noah''s time until the flood came and took them away. Jesus said no one knows the day or hour, but watchfulness is required. Jesus said the gospel of the Kingdom would be proclaimed in the whole world as a testimony to all nations. Jesus warned those in Judea to flee immediately when the abomination of desolation appears. Jesus said the sign of the Son of Man will appear in heaven before his coming. Jesus used the fig tree as a picture of recognizing the nearness of what he foretold. Wars, famines, and earthquakes were described as the beginning of labor pains, not the end itself. Jesus warned that deceptive leaders would perform signs and wonders in an attempt to deceive. Jesus said his coming would be unmistakable, like lightning flashing across the sky. Jesus said his angels would gather his elect from the four winds. Jesus said those days would be shortened for the sake of the elect, otherwise no flesh would be saved. Jesus stressed unexpectedness with the examples of Noah''s days and a thief coming when the householder does not expect him. The faithful servant is found doing his assigned work of caring for the household. The wicked servant is cut off in judgment because his behavior exposed unbelief and abuse. Their questions about the temple and the end prompted the Olivet discourse. Jesus warned that because lawlessness increases, the love of many will grow cold. Jesus used the paired examples to show the sudden and dividing character of his coming. Jesus repeatedly called for readiness and watchfulness because the timing is unknown. Jesus told a parable about ten virgins waiting for the bridegroom. Five virgins were wise and brought extra oil, while five were foolish. The master entrusted different amounts of talents to his servants. The Son of Man separates the nations as a shepherd separates sheep from goats. The wise virgins were prepared with extra oil when the bridegroom delayed. Once the prepared virgins entered, the door was shut and the foolish ones were left outside. The fearful servant buried the one talent instead of using it faithfully. Jesus said whatever they did for the least of these, they did for him. At midnight the announcement came that the bridegroom was arriving. The faithful servants were commended and invited into their master''s joy. The wicked servant justified his inactivity by accusing his master of hardness. The sheep are set on the right hand and the goats on the left. The wise virgins emphasized preparedness that could not be borrowed at the last moment. The master removed the unused talent from the wicked servant and gave it to the most fruitful servant. The goats are condemned because their failure to love the needy revealed rejection of the King. Jesus lists practical deeds of compassion as evidence of loyalty to him. The lesson of the parable is readiness because the exact time is unknown. The master declared the principle of increase for faithful stewardship and loss for fruitless neglect. The righteous were surprised, showing they had served from genuine compassion rather than self-display. Jesus ends the chapter with a final division into eternal life and eternal punishment. Judas went to the chief priests and agreed to betray Jesus for thirty pieces of silver. Jesus gathered with his disciples to eat the Passover meal. Jesus went to Gethsemane and prayed there in anguish before his arrest. Peter denied Jesus three times, just as Jesus had predicted. A woman anointed Jesus with very costly ointment, and he said she had prepared him for burial. Jesus gave the bread to the disciples and identified it with his body. Jesus gave the cup as a covenant sign pointing to his sacrificial death. Judas gave the agreed sign by kissing Jesus. Judas received thirty pieces of silver for agreeing to betray Jesus. Jesus quoted Scripture and said the disciples would all be made to stumble that night. Jesus took Peter and the two sons of Zebedee deeper into the garden while the others waited. Jesus rejected violent rescue and submitted to the Father''s plan. Jesus said her act was fitting because it anticipated his burial and would be remembered wherever the gospel is preached. Jesus prayed honestly about the coming suffering while fully submitting to the Father''s will. The false witnesses twisted Jesus'' words about the temple. Jesus affirmed his identity and spoke of future exaltation, which the high priest treated as blasphemy. Matthew records that after singing a hymn, they went out to the Mount of Olives. Peter insisted he would remain loyal even if all the others fell away. Jesus said he could ask the Father for angelic help, but the Scriptures had to be fulfilled. Peter''s bitter weeping showed grief after he realized Jesus'' words had come true. Pilate offered to release Jesus or Barabbas, and the crowd chose Barabbas. The soldiers compelled Simon of Cyrene to carry Jesus'' cross. A darkness came over all the land during those hours of the crucifixion. Joseph of Arimathea asked for Jesus'' body and laid it in his own new tomb. After returning the silver and confessing his sin, Judas went and hanged himself. Pilate''s wife sent word because she had suffered much in a dream because of Jesus. The accusation posted over Jesus'' head read, ''This is Jesus, the King of the Jews.'' At Jesus'' death the veil of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom. Pilate symbolically washed his hands before the crowd while handing Jesus over. The soldiers mocked Jesus as king by dressing him in a robe and pressing a crown of thorns on his head. Jesus cried out with words from Psalm 22 during the crucifixion. The centurion and those with him were filled with fear and confessed Jesus as God''s Son. The priests called the returned silver blood money and used it to buy a burial field for strangers. They gave Jesus wine mixed with gall, but he would not drink it after tasting it. Matthew records an extraordinary sign in which tombs opened and many holy ones were raised. Remembering Jesus'' prediction, they requested a guard to prevent a resurrection claim. The stirred-up crowd demanded crucifixion instead of Jesus'' release. Golgotha is explained as ''Place of a Skull.'' The mockers taunted Jesus to save himself and come down from the cross. Matthew names these women as witnesses of the crucifixion from a distance. Matthew names Mary Magdalene and the other Mary as the women who came to the tomb. The angel announced that Jesus was not in the tomb because he had risen. Both the angel and Jesus said the disciples would see him in Galilee. In the Great Commission, Jesus commanded the disciples to make disciples of all nations. Matthew reports a great earthquake as the angel descended and rolled away the stone. The guards trembled in fear and became like dead men when the angel appeared. Jesus met the women and greeted them with a word of joy. Jesus instructed the apostles to baptize in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit. The angel showed them the empty place and then sent them to tell the disciples. The women were told to announce the resurrection and the meeting in Galilee. The chief priests bribed the soldiers to spread the theft story. Matthew says the disciples worshiped Jesus, though some hesitated or doubted. The leaders promised to satisfy Pilate and keep the soldiers safe if the story reached him. Jesus grounded the commission in his universal authority. The commission includes ongoing teaching in obedience to Jesus'' commands. Jesus ended Matthew with a promise of his continual presence. The women responded to the risen Jesus with worship. Matthew places the risen Jesus'' meeting with the eleven on a mountain in Galilee. Matthew notes that the bribed report spread widely among the Jews. Jesus'' commission centers on making disciples through baptism and teaching obedience.'
